## Context
The isolation score computes mean cosine distance to k nearest EN-North neighbors.
EN-North has ~22K works; other quadrants have ~1K-4K. Higher density means
mechanically lower kNN distances for EN-North self-comparisons. The metric
therefore overstates isolation for minority quadrants regardless of semantic content.

This was flagged as a blocking issue (M6) by the statistics reviewer.

## Actions
1. Implement density-normalized isolation: subsample EN-North to match target
   quadrant size before computing kNN distances. Repeat 100x, report mean.
2. Alternative: use a null model — shuffle language/geography labels, recompute
   isolation scores, compare observed vs. null distribution.
3. Update analyze_multilingual.py with both approaches.
4. Write tests.

## Test
test_analyze_multilingual.py::test_density_normalized_isolation passes.
Subsampled isolation scores differ meaningfully from naive scores.

## Exit criteria
Report includes both naive and density-corrected isolation scores.
Difference between them is characterized (if small, naive is fine; if large,
density correction is essential and the paper uses corrected scores).
